# RFC: WATCH Command for Chabi

## Overview
WATCH is a blocking command that allows clients to subscribe to change events for a specific key or a subset of a complex data structure (e.g., a field within a hash). While the watch is active, the server streams events to the client as the watched data changes. The client can keep the connection open to receive updates in real time.

Primary use cases include:
- Building reactive features (live dashboards, tails of config changes, cache invalidation hooks).
- Debugging and observability of data mutations in development environments.

This RFC defines the user-facing command, event format, semantics, and an implementation sketch aligned with Chabi’s architecture.

## Command Syntax (MVP)
- WATCH KEY <key>
- WATCH HASH <hash>
- WATCH HASH <hash>.<field>
- WATCH LIST <list>
- WATCH SET <set>
- WATCH SET <set>.<member>

Notes:
- The command is blocking; after the initial acknowledgment, the server streams events until the client closes the connection or the server terminates the watch (e.g., on timeout in future extensions).
- Watching a non-existent key/hash/list/set/field/member is allowed; the watch remains active and the client will receive events if/when the value is created.

## Examples

Scenario: key datatype

> SET k value
1
> GET k
"value"

We monitor the change on KEY 'k'
> WATCH KEY k
(WAITING FOR UPDATES ...)

> SET k newValue
1

We got an update while WATCH is active
> WATCH KEY k
(WAITING FOR UPDATES ...)
newValue [${CURRENT_TIMESTAMP}]

------

Scenario: hash datatype

> HSET users u1 hello
1
> HGET users u1
"hello"

Watch a single field
> WATCH HASH users.u1
(WAITING FOR UPDATES ...)

Watch the entire hash map (all fields)
> WATCH HASH users
(WAITING FOR UPDATES ...)

> HSET users u1 world
1

We got updates on active watch commands
> WATCH HASH users.u1
(WAITING FOR UPDATES ...)
world [${CURRENT_TIMESTAMP}]

> WATCH HASH users
(WAITING FOR UPDATES ...)
u1:world [${CURRENT_TIMESTAMP}]

------

Scenario: set datatype

> SADD colors red
1
> SMEMBERS colors
1) "red"

Watch the entire set
> WATCH SET colors
(WAITING FOR UPDATES ...)

Add and remove members
> SADD colors blue
1
> SREM colors red
1

While watch is active
> WATCH SET colors
(WAITING FOR UPDATES ...)
added:red [${CURRENT_TIMESTAMP}]
added:blue [${CURRENT_TIMESTAMP}]
removed:red [${CURRENT_TIMESTAMP}]

Watch a specific member presence
> WATCH SET colors.red
(WAITING FOR UPDATES ...)
> SADD colors red
1
present [${CURRENT_TIMESTAMP}]
> SREM colors red
1
absent [${CURRENT_TIMESTAMP}]

------

Scenario: list datatype

> LPUSH tasks t1
1
> RPUSH tasks t2
2
> LRANGE tasks 0 -1
1) "t1"
2) "t2"

Watch the list for pushes/pops
> WATCH LIST tasks
(WAITING FOR UPDATES ...)

Mutate the list
> LPUSH tasks t0
3
> RPOP tasks
"t2"

While watch is active
> WATCH LIST tasks
(WAITING FOR UPDATES ...)
lpush:t0 len=3 [${CURRENT_TIMESTAMP}]
rpop:t2 len=2 [${CURRENT_TIMESTAMP}]

------

## Event Model
Each change to the watched target generates an event. In the MVP, events are delivered as human-readable lines for CLI users and as RESP arrays for protocol clients.

- Text form (CLI):
  - KEY scope: <value> [<timestamp_ms>]
  - HASH field scope: <field_value> [<timestamp_ms>]
  - HASH map scope: <field>:<field_value> [<timestamp_ms>]
  - SET scope (whole set): added:<member> [<timestamp_ms>] or removed:<member> [<timestamp_ms>]
  - SET member scope: present [<timestamp_ms>] or absent [<timestamp_ms>]
  - LIST scope: <op>:<value> len=<new_len> [<timestamp_ms>] where <op> ∈ {lpush, rpush, lpop, rpop}

- RESP form (protocol):
  [
    "event",                 // literal
    <event_type>,             // e.g., "set", "del", "expire", "hset", "hdel", "sadd", "srem", "lpush", "rpush", "lpop", "rpop"
    <scope>,                  // "KEY" | "HASH" | "SET" | "LIST"
    <key>,                    // key/hash/set/list name
    <subkey_or_empty>,        // field for HASH, member for SET-member watch, "L"|"R" for LIST side on push/pop, or "" if not applicable
    <value_or_empty>,         // value after mutation (or popped value), or member added/removed (for SET), or "" if deleted/absent
    <timestamp_ms>,           // integer milliseconds since UNIX_EPOCH
    <extra_or_empty>          // optional: e.g., new_len for LIST mutations (as stringified integer) or ""
  ]

Event types (MVP):
- KEY scope: set, del, expire.
- HASH scope: hset, hdel.
- SET scope: sadd, srem.
- LIST scope: lpush, rpush, lpop, rpop.

Notes:
- For delete/expire events where there is no value, value_or_empty is "" in RESP and omitted (or shown as empty) in text form.
- For LIST events, extra_or_empty SHOULD carry the new length; for other scopes, it SHOULD be "".
- Timestamps are server-generated as milliseconds since UNIX_EPOCH.

## Semantics
- Ordering: Events for a given key (or hash/field, set, list) are emitted in the order mutations are applied.
- Delivery guarantees: Best-effort real-time delivery over a single TCP connection. If the client does not read fast enough and the server’s internal buffers fill, the server may drop the connection.
- Scope matching:
  - WATCH KEY <k>: emits mutations that affect the value at key "k" (set, del, expire).
  - WATCH HASH <h>.<f>: emits mutations that affect a specific field "f" in hash "h" (hset/hdel).
  - WATCH HASH <h>: emits mutations of any field in hash "h". Event includes the field name.
  - WATCH SET <s>: emits sadd/srem for any member in set "s"; value is the member.
  - WATCH SET <s>.<m>: emits presence updates for member "m" in set "s" as present/absent transitions.
  - WATCH LIST <l>: emits push/pop mutations (lpush, rpush, lpop, rpop) for list "l"; value is the pushed/popped element, extra_or_empty carries new length.
- Existence: Watching non-existent targets is allowed; events are produced if/when they are created.
- Blocking nature: The connection is dedicated to the watch stream while active. Other commands on the same connection are not processed until the watch ends (disconnect).

## Errors
- Wrong arity/syntax: Return a protocol error (e.g., ERR wrong number of arguments).
- Unsupported scope: Return ERR unsupported scope.

## Implementation Sketch
- Registration: Maintain per-scope registries using the existing pub/sub channels map (e.g., key→subscribers, hash→subscribers, set→subscribers, set.member→subscribers, list→subscribers). Each subscriber holds a Sender for outbound events.
- Emission points: On every mutation path, publish to the relevant channels:
  - KEY k: set/del/expire → watchers of KEY k
  - HASH h.f: hset/hdel → watchers of HASH h.f and watchers of HASH h
  - SET s: sadd/srem → watchers of SET s; also if watching SET s.m, emit present/absent when membership flips
  - LIST l: lpush/rpush/lpop/rpop → watchers of LIST l (include side and new length)
- Timestamp: Use SystemTime::now().duration_since(UNIX_EPOCH).as_millis() for event timestamps.
- Backpressure: Use bounded channels; if send fails due to a closed or overwhelmed receiver, remove the subscriber.
- Threading: The WATCH handler spawns a task that forwards channel messages to the client connection until closed.

## Performance Considerations
- O(1) overhead per mutation per attached watcher.
- Memory overhead proportional to the number of active watchers.
- To avoid head-of-line blocking, use per-watcher buffers (bounded mpsc channels) and clean up on send failures.

## Backward/Forward Compatibility
- New command; no impact on existing commands.
- Future extensions can be added without breaking MVP behavior.

## Future Extensions (Non-goals for MVP)
- Patterns: WATCH KEYPATTERN <glob> (subscribe to a set of keys via glob/prefix).
- Additional data types: LIST index/segment watchers (e.g., <list>.<index> or slices), ZSET support, STREAMS.
- Filters: --events=… to select a subset of events; --initial to send the current value snapshot.
- Timeouts: WATCH … TIMEOUT <ms> to auto-terminate after inactivity or fixed period.
- Batching: Periodic coalescing of rapid consecutive updates.
- Acks/replay: Sequencing and limited replay on reconnect.

## Testing Plan
- Unit tests: Ensure event emission on all mutation paths for keys, hashes, sets, and lists; verify ordering per scope.
- Integration tests:
  - WATCH KEY on non-existent key, then SET → receives set event.
  - WATCH HASH <h>.<f>, HSET multiple times → receives ordered updates.
  - WATCH HASH <h>, HSET/HDEL different fields → receives field-tagged events.
  - WATCH SET <s>, SADD/SREM various members → receives add/remove events.
  - WATCH SET <s>.<m>, SADD/SREM <m> → receives present/absent transitions.
  - WATCH LIST <l>, LPUSH/RPUSH/LPOP/RPOP → receives correct operations with new length.
  - Expiration path: set TTL then observe expire event (when supported by the scheduler).
- Load tests: Many watchers on the same targets and many concurrent mutations to validate stability and cleanup on slow consumers.
